This repository contains zero bytes of Broadcom or nexmon firmware. The patch
table in patches/inplace-v7.txt describes byte-level modifications applied at
install time to a firmware file already present on the user's system. The
installer refuses to run unless the on-disk firmware matches a SHA-256 listed
in patches/manifest.json.

This stability patch is layered on top of monitor-mode patches provided by
nexmon (https://github.com/seemoo-lab/nexmon, GPLv3). nexmon is not
redistributed by this repository. The supported input firmware is the
nexmon-patched brcmfmac43436-sdio.bin shipped by jayofelony's pwnagotchi image
(https://github.com/jayofelony/pwnagotchi). Other sources of nexmon-patched
firmware may also work if their SHA-256 happens to match a manifest entry; we
do not test or support any path other than the jayofelony image.

Legal disclaimer: the legal status of distributing byte-level patch facts
about a proprietary firmware without distributing the firmware itself is
unsettled. We are not lawyers. We have not received legal advice. This
repository is offered in good faith on the basis that (1) no firmware bytes
are shipped, (2) the patch facts are necessary to interoperate with the
hardware as documented in the public Raspberry Pi Foundation firmware
package, and (3) the upstream nexmon project has distributed similar
modifications publicly since 2015 without takedown. If a rights-holder asks
us to take this repository down, we will comply.

Tamper evidence: as of v1, this repository is unsigned. The installer
hard-codes a MANIFEST_TRUSTED_HASHES table that pins every hash referenced
by every manifest entry -- input firmware, output firmware, patch file, and
both userspace binaries (aarch64 and armhf) -- and refuses to apply any
manifest whose hashes do not match that table. The installer also recomputes
the actual on-disk SHA-256 of the patch file and userspace binary it is
about to use, before using them. This is a tripwire against single-file
edits to the repo and against post-clone manipulation. It is NOT a
substitute for cryptographic signing: an attacker who can write both
manifest.json AND install.sh in the same commit defeats it. Real signing
(signed git tags + tarball release process) is filed as a v1.1 release
blocker.

Hardware target: Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W only. The installer will refuse to run
on any other model.

This is a community contribution. It is not affiliated with Raspberry Pi Ltd.,
Broadcom Inc., or the nexmon project.
